Dreaming big on these bucketlist destinations for 2023! ✨ My friends keep asking where they should go this year & this is where I keep telling them 👇🏽 🏝️ French Polynesia: swim with whales, some of the best diving in the world, pristine lagoons & waterfalls. Don’t miss Moorea, Bora Bora & Rangiroa. 🐪 Oman: If you love Morocco you will LOVE Oman (plus you can skip all the tourist lines because Oman is still fairly untravelled). Oman’s architecture is out of this world, it’s so naturally beautiful I could cry(!!), the people are so welcoming & its easy (& safe) to do a road trip.  🌵 Mexico: Tacos, surfing, jungle vibes, happy humans, waterfalls, incredible food & pristine beaches. Although I love the East Coast (Tulum etc) I recommend trying to West Coast & including Todos Santos & Sayulita on your itinerary! 🐢 Seychelles: Giant tortoises, crazy blue water, tiny islands to explore & a tropical vibe like no other! 🦘Australia: Snorkel the Great Barrier Reef, eat the yummiest vegan food in Byron Bay, explore the Cape Le Grand National Park in Esperance, rent a boat & sail the Whitsundays & go island / waterfall hopping in Far North Queensland. One of the best countries in the entire world!! 🐠 Maldives: A water wonderland & ultimate heaven on earth. Tiny islands, world class snorkelling / diving & luxury resorts to rival the best in the world! #bucketlistadventures #2023travel #2023goals #traveltheworld #bucketlisttravel #beautifuldestinations #bucketlisters #liveyourpassion #travelgoal #travelthroughtheworld #traveltok

Could you do it? 90 years old and still making the youngsters look like amateurs. In a tucked-away corner of Romania, where time seemed to have frozen in a poignant dance with tradition, I stumbled upon a living testament to the indomitable spirit of life. A grandma, a matriarch in the heart of her village, carving poetry with a scythe in her “batatura,” the courtyard that cradled generations of stories. This wasn’t just about cutting grass; it was an ode to survival etched in every swing of the weathered scythe. An elderly woman, a silhouette against the backdrop of rolling hills and rustic charm, maneuvering a tool almost as ancient as her. The rhythmic cadence of the blade carving through the grass sang a ballad of resilience that transcended the boundaries of time. It was as if the scythe itself held the secrets of a thousand lifetimes, whispered through the hands of those who had faced hardship head-on. In the heart of Romanian villages, where the air is heavy with the tales of survival and shared history, the elders cultivate more than just crops. Our grandma, with her face etched in lines of laughter and wisdom, was a guardian of a fading dialect – the language of resilience, of grit. The scythe, a silent protagonist in this tale, became a bridge connecting the elderly to the present, a tool passed down like an heirloom, carrying the weight of memories in its worn blade.  As she honed that blade with a special stone and cleaned it with freshly cut grass, it wasn’t just about maintaining a tool; it was a ritual, a communion with a way of life that had weathered storms and stood resilient against the test of time. Could you do it? 90 years old and still making the youngsters look like amateurs. In a tucked-away corner of Romania, where time seemed to have frozen in a poignant dance with tradition, I stumbled upon a living testament to the indomitable spirit of life. A grandma, a matriarch in the heart of her village, carving poetry with a scythe in her “batatura,” the courtyard that cradled generations of stories. This wasn’t just about cutting grass; it was an ode to survival etched in every swing of the weathered scythe. An elderly woman, a silhouette against the backdrop of rolling hills and rustic charm, maneuvering a tool almost as ancient as her. The rhythmic cadence of the blade carving through the grass sang a ballad of resilience that transcended the boundaries of time. It was as if the scythe itself held the secrets of a thousand lifetimes, whispered through the hands of those who had faced hardship head-on. In the heart of Romanian villages, where the air is heavy with the tales of survival and shared history, the elders cultivate more than just crops. Our grandma, with her face etched in lines of laughter and wisdom, was a guardian of a fading dialect – the language of resilience, of grit. The scythe, a silent protagonist in this tale, became a bridge connecting the elderly to the present, a tool passed down like an heirloom, carrying the weight of memories in its worn blade.  As she honed that blade with a special stone and cleaned it with freshly cut grass, it wasn’t just about maintaining a tool; it was a ritual, a communion with a way of life that had weathered storms and stood resilient against the test of time. Have you ever seen this before? Wander deep into the untamed heart of the Carpathian wilderness, where the air pulses with the primal vibes of a true king—meet cerbul, the stag. This beast, a living emblem of unbridled beauty, roams Romania’s wild landscapes, casting an ancient spell on those who dare to step into its kingdom. Picture the stag, a majestic silhouette against the backdrop of lush undergrowth, its antlers soaring into the heavens. It moves with the swagger of a guardian of the wild, a noble entity that demands respect with every elegant stride. Witness the spectacle as it sheds and regrows its antlers—a natural show that echoes the rhythmic pulse of these ageless forests. As this majestic creature traverses the rugged terrain, it carries more than just its imposing physicality. It’s a living legend, woven into the very soul of Romania through tales and folklore. The stag isn’t just a symbol of the wild; it embodies resilience, strength, and the delicate interplay between humanity and the wild unknown. Encounters with the cerb forge a connection to the primal spirit of the Carpathian wilderness—a symphony where history’s echoes harmonize with nature’s unyielding grace, creating a rhythm that resonates with every beat of the heart. How would you articulate the essence of the stag? Could you do it? 90 years old and still making the youngsters look like amateurs. In a tucked-away corner of Romania, where time seemed to have frozen in a poignant dance with tradition, I stumbled upon a living testament to the indomitable spirit of life. A grandma, a matriarch in the heart of her village, carving poetry with a scythe in her “batatura,” the courtyard that cradled generations of stories. This wasn’t just about cutting grass; it was an ode to survival etched in every swing of the weathered scythe. An elderly woman, a silhouette against the backdrop of rolling hills and rustic charm, maneuvering a tool almost as ancient as her. The rhythmic cadence of the blade carving through the grass sang a ballad of resilience that transcended the boundaries of time. It was as if the scythe itself held the secrets of a thousand lifetimes, whispered through the hands of those who had faced hardship head-on. In the heart of Romanian villages, where the air is heavy with the tales of survival and shared history, the elders cultivate more than just crops. Our grandma, with her face etched in lines of laughter and wisdom, was a guardian of a fading dialect – the language of resilience, of grit. The scythe, a silent protagonist in this tale, became a bridge connecting the elderly to the present, a tool passed down like an heirloom, carrying the weight of memories in its worn blade. As she honed that blade with a special stone and cleaned it with freshly cut grass, it wasn’t just about maintaining a tool; it was a ritual, a communion with a way of life that had weathered storms and stood resilient against the test of time. I WILL BE POSTING MY CONTENT ABOUT UKRAINE IN THE NEXT DAYS, PLEASE FOLLOW UP! 🫶🏽 Yes, I visited Ukraine. 🇺🇦 I haven’t been posting or telling hardly anyone about it, but I’ll finally start sharing my Ukraine content now. 🥳 I ended up staying in Kyiv for 3 weeks! It’s unbelievable I have had this experience and was able to see this country. It definitely wasn’t the best time to visit, but this made my stay even more unique. I’m still processing all that I’ve seen, realizing I lived in a war zone. I have tried to document as much as possible and can’t wait to share it all with you!  My anxiety and stress levels were high, and I almost didn’t go. So this experience just showed me once again that life begins outside of your comfort zone. 🙏🏽 Ukrainians are unique and beautiful people and I am grateful for the opportunity to witness the culture and daily life of this country! follow @hellobylouis for more travel insights ✨ #visitukraine #ukrainetoday #visitkyiv #exploreukraine #warinukraine #backpackingadventures

Is it the most light weight? No.  Will it do the job? Yes 🙌🏼  Hiking the highly sort after Jatbula Trail in June and needed to upgrade a few pieces of my gear.  I really wanted to invest in something like sea to summit, MSR or Big Agnes but the budget didn’t allow this year.  However, I’ve picked up this banger from @Anaconda  It’s the Mountain Designs Redline 2P 3 season tent.  I use the wide Alton Goods sleeping pad and it fits that and a slimmer pad but it’s a tight squeeze. I am travelling with a friend so we’ll see how that goes but usually it’s just me and my doggo @Natalya & Hayda  Initial thoughts are that even without actually reading the instructions it was simple to set up in only 5 mins. Has great head room so it’s a tent you can sit up in. Has great ventilation that I can see. It is on the heavier side at 2.1kgs but I’ll be sharing the load on it for the first trip.  #hiking #hikingadventures #hikingwithdogs #jatbulatrail #hikingaustralia #backpackinggear #backpackingadventures #backpackingaustralia #hikingtent #backpackingtent #girlswhohike #girlbackpacker #girlshike #girlswhocamp #cuinthent

After 1 month in Sri Lanka, not including flights, this is what we’ve spent per person… 🏠 £143 on accommodation - less than £5 per night on average! 🛺 £64 on transport which includes buses, trains and tuk tuks 🍜 £437 on food - £14.50 per day on average! 🐘 £82 on activities which includes our safari and other small admission fees 💊 £32 on miscellaneous, which covers Kitt’s tattoo and random bits from the pharmacy  📞 £19.30 each on phone data for the month So, the grand total spend for Sri Lanka was £777 per person, which takes us to a fraction over £25 per person per day over 30 days!  TIPS: ✨A room based on 2 people sharing was nearly always cheaper than a hostel (if you can go without aircon, this saves $$ too!) ✨ Buying train tickets are cheaper at the station than online platforms such as 12Go - buy ahead of time to avoid them selling out! ✨ This one’s a given, but opt for local and street food to save pennies ✨ ‘Pickme’ is a very cheap way of getting taxis in Sri Lanka, and any public transport is extremely low cost! ✨ We use ‘Get Nomad’ for our phone data on an eSim - this saves time and effort (compared with local sim) and easy to top up ✨ Lots of places in Sri Lanka charge for foreigners to enter such as parks. Even some temples would charge 15x the price of locals. Often we would find other things to do that weren’t necessarily on ‘top 10’ lists How did we do?! Are you surprised or is this exactly what you expected? #srilankadaily #srilankatrip #srilankatourism #srilanka🇱🇰 #budgettraveltips #budgettravel #backpackingasia #kandysrilanka #backpackingadventures

These Banded Bull Frogs in Thailand seemed to be having a ribeting time at their social gathering whilst they kept us awake all night because of their obsurd and noisy sound. It wasn’t like anything we had ever heard before apart from maybe a large hurd of mooing cows. They were hiding amongst these logs that had been cut up that day after a tree had fell in a storm the night before and the ground was sodden with heavy rain water.  #bandedbullfrog #thaiwildlife #tropicalstorm #tropicalwildlife #weirdnoises #frogs #strangerthings #strangesounds #wildsounds #soundsofnature #adventurelife #randomthings #backpackinglife #southeastasiatravel #travelstories #backpackingadventures #unexpectedevents #backpackers #backpackingsoutheastasia #exploringtheworld #funnymoments

These Banded Bull Frogs in Thailand seemed to be having a ribeting time at their social gathering whilst they kept us awake all night because of their obsurd and noisy sound. It wasn’t like anything we had ever heard before apart from maybe a large hurd of mooing cows. They were hiding amongst these logs that had been cut up that day after a tree had fell in a storm the night before and the ground was sodden with heavy rain water.  #bandedbullfrog #thaiwildlife #tropicalstorm #tropicalwildlife #weirdnoises #frogs #strangerthings #strangesounds #wildsounds #soundsofnature #adventurelife #randomthings #backpackinglife #southeastasiatravel #travelstories #backpackingadventures #unexpectedevents #backpackers #backpackingsoutheastasia #exploringtheworld #funnymoments

Nuit compliquée, on a eu très très froid ! Réveil 5h pour 6h de rando bien intense, on est mort mort !!! On a passé la rando avec Manolo notre nouveau meilleur copain, qui a été bien sympa surtout dans les parties de désescalade à la corde ou j’étais trop petite pour atteindre les prises ! Et aussi pour les blagues  Encore une journée luxe : douche chaude et lessive sèche !!!! Pietra Piana tu nous régales🫶🏼 On a dormi une grosse partie de l’aprem, on a dîné tôt nos classiques pâtes sauce tomate, grosse casserole de tisane er au lit à 20h10 !  #GR20 #Randonnée #Aventure #Montagne #NatureLovers #TrekLife #HikingAdventures #Corsica #OutdoorLife #TrailExperience #ExploreTheWorld #Voyageurs #Dénivelé #PassionRando #Randonneurs #GR20Challenge #MontagneAddict #WildCamping #OffTheGrid #BackpackingAdventures #EpicViews

🌎 making travel breaks and rest days is SO important! don‘t switch locations too often and stay in one place longer.  🌎 don‘t feel bad about your anti-social days where you just lay in bed and watch netflix 🌎 calling your loved ones from home from time to time is as important as making new travel friends 🌎 don’t plan too much ahead, just don‘t do it. your plans will change a thousand times!  🌎budget extra because there will be expenses you didn’t think of or problems you need to solve with money (unfortunately)  🌎 streetfood over restaurants! forever and always. it‘s authentic, cheap and just unbelievable yummyyy 🌎 sometimes not everything goes as planned, you will make mistakes and you‘ll learn from them.  remember you will laugh about these days and they gonna be THE BEST stories to tell (believe me I have tons of these stories haha)  #travelhack #traveltips #travelblog #solotravel #solofemaletraveler #femaleempowerment #femalepower #solotraveler #traveltips #travelinspiration #traveler #solofemale #grlpwr #grlpwr #mindsetmatters #thepowerofdreams #travelmistakes #traveltipsandtricks #easytravel #travel #reisetipps #reisetipps #weltreise #weltreisende #nomad #nomadstories #backpacker #backpackinglife #backpackinghacks #backpackers #backpackingadventures

As part of the FutureSense Group, at the heart of everything GapGuru does is our charity, the FutureSense Foundation. The FutureSense Foundation is a registered charity that supports community development in some of the world’s poorest regions. The charity is aligned with the United Nations Global Goals for Sustainable Development and is committed to implementing long-term programs where ethical and sustainable impact is at the core. With a team based year-round in each country, FutureSense works hand-in-hand with the local communities, delivering programs that address the actual challenges they face to make a long-lasting impact. Our partnership with FutureSense ensures that anyone embarking on a GapGuru program becomes part of something bigger and helps to deliver truly sustainable community impact. #gapyears #gapyear #travelabroad #discoveringtheworld #wanderingsoul #discovermore #travelwithpurpose #roadlesstraveled #travellife #starttheadventure #backpackingadventures #backpackinglife #solotravels #summerbreak #adventureisoutthere #travellling #elephants#traveloverseas #studentsabroad

WHY SHOULD YOU TRAVEL??  📍Barrel - Siargao, Philippines  Simply because you’ll have memories like this to look back on and think ‘wow, that really happened’.  Making meaningful connections on the road is the best thing ever! We met Sziszi and Matteo in Thailand. Our paths crossed multiple times as most travellers do and we got on super well. We stayed in touch and before we knew it, they took a really long travel day to come spend 10 days with us in Siargao Philippines.  This was around the 4month mark for us of our travels so it was pretty nice to have familiar faces to spend a good amount of time together with. And they may or may not be the reason why I will hold of the Philippine so close to my heart.  I know for sure that our paths will cross again!!  Travels are when build your story, and it’s gonna be a bit boring if you’re always in the same spot, so get out there, go!!  #travelmemories #travelstories #backpackingadventures #siargao #philippines🇵🇭

Ja die Zeit auf Sri Lanka war schön, aber auch intensiv. Und vieles hier ist anders, als zuhause in Deutschland, weshalb manches ungewohnt für uns war und wir uns auch in dieser kurzen Zeit nicht dran gewöhnen konnten oder wollten.  Hier unsere 3 Dinge, die wir nicht vermissen werden.  Nr.1 das Plastik am Strand, auch Sri Lanka ist hiervon nicht verschont geblieben und an vielen Ecken wird Plastikmüll angespült. Leider wird auch beim Einkaufen bzw Alltag noch sehr viel Plastik verbraucht. Nr.2 häufig hatten wir beim Essen Sandkörner zwischen den Zähnen. Wir vermuten, dass es oft von den Frühlingszwiebeln bzw. dem Lauch kam. Das tat schon manchmal beim plötzlichen aufbeißen sehr weh. Nr. 3 die Busse dort waren wirklich verrückt und wir hatten teilweise echt Angst vor ihnen. Sie hupen direkt neben dir als Fußgänger mit völlig übertönten Hupen, das sorgt richtig für Adrenalinausschüttung. Ja so ein Urlaub in einem fremden Land bringt auch neue Erfahrungen und dafür sind wir trotzdem dankbar, auch wenn wir sie definitiv nicht vermissen werden. #coupleswhotravel #traveltogether #travelgirl #travellife #vacation #travelgoals #creativetravelcouples #naturephotography #traveltips #travelcommunity #travelislife #seetheworld #travelcouplegoals #adventurecouple #backpackingcouple #backpacksoutheastasia #backpackingadventures #solotraveler #shareexperiences #sorrytosay

Und vieles hier ist anders, als zuhause in Deutschland, weshalb manches ungewohnt für uns war und wir uns auch in dieser kurzen Zeit nicht dran gewöhnen konnten oder wollten.  Hier unsere 3 Dinge, die wir nicht vermissen werden.  Nr.1 das Plastik am Strand, auch Sri Lanka ist hiervon nicht verschont geblieben und an vielen Ecken wird Plastikmüll angespült. Leider wird auch beim Einkaufen bzw Alltag noch sehr viel Plastik verbraucht. Nr.2 häufig hatten wir beim Essen Sandkörner zwischen den Zähnen. Wir vermuten, dass es oft von den Frühlingszwiebeln bzw. dem Lauch kam. Das tat schon manchmal beim plötzlichen aufbeißen sehr weh. Nr. 3 die Busse dort waren wirklich verrückt und wir hatten teilweise echt Angst vor ihnen. Sie hupen direkt neben dir als Fußgänger mit völlig übertönten Hupen, das sorgt richtig für Adrenalinausschüttung. Ja so ein Urlaub in einem fremden Land bringt auch neue Erfahrungen und dafür sind wir trotzdem dankbar, auch wenn wir sie definitiv nicht vermissen werden. #coupleswhotravel #traveltogether #travelgirl #travellife #vacation #travelgoals #creativetravelcouples #naturephotography #traveltips #travelcommunity #travelislife #seetheworld #travelcouplegoals #adventurecouple #backpackingcouple #backpacksoutheastasia #backpackingadventures #solotraveler #shareexperiences #sorrytosay

Kennst du diesen Ort? Ta Prohm, auch bekannt als der Tomb-Raider-Tempel ist eine verlassene Tempelanlage aus dem 12. Jhdt im Westen Kambodschas nahe der Stadt Siem Reap. Der Tempel, welcher ursprünglich als Kloster und Universität diente, ist bekannt für seine einzigartige Atmosphäre. In dieser Anlage verbindet sich die alte Stätte mit der Natur auf spektakuläre Weise. Gigantische Bäume, unter anderem Würgefeigen wachsen mittlerweile auf den Mauern und haben große Teile des Bauwerkes mit Ihren kräftigen Wurzeln umschlungen. Ta Prohm wurde im Vergleich zu anderen Tempeln nicht restauriert, um die Ursprünglichkeit beizubehalten. Dank dieser Verschmelzung mit der Natur, diente er 2001 als Kulisse für das Videospiel Tomb Raider und die Abenteuer von Lara Croft.  Ta Prohm gehört mit vielen anderen Tempeln zusammen die größte Religiöse Stätte rund um Angkor Wat in Kambodscha, die auf jeden Fall einen Besuch wert ist. I'll be reviewing running routes from all over the world. Running has been my daily ritual for the past ten years, helping me through some tough times. For the last fourteen months, I've been on an incredible journey across sixteen countries, and no matter where I am, running is a must for me. However, I've noticed a lack of detailed information about running routes, especially in less-traveled locations. That's why I'm creating a series of videos reviewing hundreds of different runs from various places around the globe. In each video, I'll share insights about the location and the route itself. I'll only feature routes I'd personally recommend—whether they're fast, flat, and long, or a challenging uphill with breathtaking views.  These routes aren't just great runs; they're also fantastic ways to explore new places. If any of the routes catch your eye, just comment "run" on the video, and I'll share the Strava route with you. You don't need to be super fit or fast to try these routes—I'm not! I do enjoy long distances, so you'll find everything from 5Ks to marathons in my reviews. I'll be reviewing running routes from all over the world. Running has been my daily ritual for the past ten years, helping me through some tough times. For the last fourteen months, I've been on an incredible journey across sixteen countries, and no matter where I am, running is a must for me. However, I've noticed a lack of detailed information about running routes, especially in less-traveled locations. That's why I'm creating a series of videos reviewing hundreds of different runs from various places around the globe. In each video, I'll share insights about the location and the route itself. I'll only feature routes I'd personally recommend—whether they're fast, flat, and long, or a challenging uphill with breathtaking views.  These routes aren't just great runs; they're also fantastic ways to explore new places. If any of the routes catch your eye, just comment "run" on the video, and I'll share the Strava route with you. You don't need to be super fit or fast to try these routes—I'm not! I do enjoy long distances, so you'll find everything from 5Ks to marathons in my reviews. Kennst du diesen Ort? Ta Prohm, auch bekannt als der Tomb-Raider-Tempel ist eine verlassene Tempelanlage aus dem 12. Jhdt im Westen Kambodschas nahe der Stadt Siem Reap. Der Tempel, welcher ursprünglich als Kloster und Universität diente, ist bekannt für seine einzigartige Atmosphäre. In dieser Anlage verbindet sich die alte Stätte mit der Natur auf spektakuläre Weise. Gigantische Bäume, unter anderem Würgefeigen wachsen mittlerweile auf den Mauern und haben große Teile des Bauwerkes mit Ihren kräftigen Wurzeln umschlungen. Ta Prohm wurde im Vergleich zu anderen Tempeln nicht restauriert, um die Ursprünglichkeit beizubehalten. Dank dieser Verschmelzung mit der Natur, diente er 2001 als Kulisse für das Videospiel Tomb Raider und die Abenteuer von Lara Croft.  Ta Prohm gehört mit vielen anderen Tempeln zusammen die größte Religiöse Stätte rund um Angkor Wat in Kambodscha, die auf jeden Fall einen Besuch wert ist.
